06082nam a22008175i 9780824896461DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248964617 a10.1515/97808248964612doi  a(DE-B1597)649753  a(OCoLC)1355223200  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aREL0920002bisacsh04a294.3/9270951223//eng/20221215eng1 aMcRae, John R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aZen Evangelist :bShenhui, Sudden Enlightenment, and the Southern School of Chan Buddhism /cJohn R. McRae; ed. by Fedde de Vries, Robert E. Buswell, James Robson, Robert H. Sharf. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (360 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aKuroda Classics in East Asian Buddhism ;v1200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tAbbreviations and Conventions -- tIntroduction: Shenhui and the Teaching of Sudden Enlightenment -- tPart I. Texts -- tPart II. Shenhui and the Chan Tradition -- tAPPENDIX. Textual Sources -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHuineng (638–713), author and hero of the Platform Sutra, is often credited with founding the Southern school of Chan Buddhism and its radical doctrine of “sudden enlightenment.” However, manuscripts discovered at Dunhuang at the beginning of the twentieth century reveal that the real architect of the Southern school was Huineng’s student Shenhui (684–758). An ardent evangelist for his master’s teaching and a sharp critic of rival meditation teachers of his day, Shenhui was responsible for Huineng’s recognition as the “sixth patriarch,” for the promotion and eventual triumph of the sudden teaching, and for a somewhat combative style of Chan discourse that came to be known as “encounter dialogue.” Shenhui’s historical importance in the rise and success of Chan is beyond dispute, yet until now there has been no complete translation of his corpus into English.This volume brings together John McRae’s lifetime of work on the Shenhui corpus, including extensively annotated translations of all five of Shenhui’s texts discovered at Dunhuang as well as McRae’s seminal studies of Shenhui’s life, teachings, and legacy. McRae’s research explores the degree to which the received view of the Northern school teachings is a fiction created by Shenhui to score rhetorical points and that Northern and Southern teachings may have been closer to one another than the canonical narrative depicts. McRae explains Shenhui’s critical role in shaping what would later emerge as “classical Chan,” while remaining skeptical about the glowing image of Shenhui as an effective mentor and inspired revolutionary. This posthumously published book is the fulfillment of McRae’s wish to make Shenhui’s surviving writings accessible through carefully annotated English translations, allowing readers to form their own opinions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBuddhismzChinaxHistoryy581-960. 0aZen BuddhismzChinaxDoctrines. 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / Zen (see also PHILOSOPHY / Zen).2bisacsh  aBuddhism.  aChan Buddhism.  aReligion.  aShenhui.1 aBuswell, Robert E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGregory, Peter N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRobson, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRobson, James, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSharf, Robert H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSharf, Robert H., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aVries, Fedde de, eeditor.